INT. DINER - NIGHT

Neon hums. Rain needles the window. A lone WAITRESS wipes the counter for the third time.

WAITRESS
Coffee's still hot if you want it.

CUSTOMER
(looking up)
I shouldn't. Doctor's orders.

WAITRESS
Doctors don't work nights in this town.

She pours anyway. Black. No ceremony.

CUSTOMER
You always this chatty with strangers?

WAITRESS
Only the ones who look like they might tip.

EXT. DINER PARKING LOT - NIGHT

The CUSTOMER steps into the rain. Headlights crawl past on the wet road. He does not look back.

INT. DINER - NIGHT

The waitress watches the door. Wipes the counter again.

WAITRESS
Anything else?

She waits. Nobody answers. She keeps talking anyway because the rain is loud and the night is long and somebody has to fill the silence with something that sounds like a human being still works here.

WAITRESS
Sir, can I get you anything else? Pie? We have pie. Apple, cherry, something that used to be blueberry before the freezer lost power last Tuesday and nobody told me until the health inspector almost did.

She leans on the counter. Keeps going.

WAITRESS
You know what I think? I think people come in here not for the coffee and not for the pie and not for the neon that flickers like it's auditioning for a noir. They come in because somewhere between the highway and home they need a room that smells like grease and patience. That's the product. Patience by the cup.

CUSTOMER (V.O.)
I left before she finished. I still hear her.

INT. CAR - NIGHT

Wipers beat. The customer drives. City lights smear.

FADE OUT.
